Glossary
📖 Glossary for graph
context word meaning
Distance Graph metric A metric space defined over a set of points in terms of distances in a graph defined over the set, which metric space is formed if and only if the graph is connected.
Graph metric eccentricity | ε(v) the greatest distance between v and any other vertex
Graph metric radius | r the minimum eccentricity of any vertex
Graph metric diameter | d the maximum eccentricity of any vertex
Graph metric central vertex a vertex whose eccentricity is r
Graph metric peripheral vertex a vertex whose eccentricity is d
Graph metric pseudo-peripheral vertex vertices ε(v1) == ε(v2)
Graph Geodetic graph a undirected graph such that there exists a unique (unweighted) shortest path between each two vertices.
GraphDistance
⚙️ Colored nodes are Pseudo-peripheral vertices
   - Blue: Distance 3.
   - Yellow and Red: Distance 4 (Diameter) and Peripheral vertices.
⚙️ All trees are geodetic so that Pseudo-peripheral vertices in tree can be considered as Peripheral vertices.

🅰️ MinimumSpanningTree
: 💻 Complexity Class of the decision problem is P and have strong polynomial time to exact algorithm.

     : 🍡 Borůvka, Kruskal, Prim, Reverse-delete
Kruskal
⚙️ about Time Complexity
   - O( E*log(E) ) from Timsort, O(|E|) from iterating edges
   - O( α(n) ) from Union-Find data structure (Inversed Ackermann function)
⚙️ about Space Complexity
   - O (|V|) from Union-Find data structure + O(|E|) in order to iterate all edges
Best Average Worst Memory
- - E*log(E) |V| + |E| 

===== wbfw109.labs.basics.graphs.search =====
: 💻 Complexity Class of the decision problem is P and have strong polynomial time to exact algorithm.
    decision problem: to ask whether there exists a path between two nodes in a given graph.
    
    : 🍡 BFS, DFS
Glossary
📖 Glossary for Graph search
context word meaning
BigO V 'Vertex' == 'node'
BigO E 'Edge'
BigO d 'distance' from the start node
BigO b 'branching factor'; the number of children at each node
node name <upper character> Explicit node
node name <lower character> Implicit node (not specified in edges in <given node>
name search key == start node
🅰️ DfsAndBfs
BFS
Non-recursive implementation that visits from left edge to right edge
elapsed time verification
BFS with queue ['A', 'B', 'C', 'X', 'D', 'E', 'G', 'H', 'z', 'F', 'y']
⚙️ In BFS, usually a queue is needed to keep track of the child nodes that were encountered but not yet explored
     , and BFS may use hash table used to keep track of the visited vertices.
   - It could be implemented by by replacing stack with queue in depth_first_search, but that is somewhat nonstandard one.

⚙️ [Worse-case] Time complexity: O(|V| + |E|)
   - In the case that every vertex and every edge will be explored in the worst case.
   - Note that O(|E|) may vary between O(1) and O(|V|^2), depending on how sparse the input graph is.
⚙️ [Worse-case] Space complexity: O(|V|)
   - In the case that it is need to hold all vertices in the queue.

⚙️ When working with graphs that are too large to store explicitly (or infinite)
   - it is more practical to describe the complexity of breadth-first search in different terms
     : to find the nodes that are at distance d from the start node (measured in number of edge traversals), BFS takes O(b^d) time and memory
     : 🛍️ e.g. Is the Worse-case the complexity of complete binary tree is O(2^d)
Best Average Worst Memory
- - |V| + |E| = b^d |V| = b^d
DFS
Non-recursive implementation that visits from right edges to left edge
name explored order
DFS with stack ['A', 'X', 'z', 'C', 'H', 'y', 'G', 'B', 'E', 'F', 'D']
⚙️ In DFS, usually a stack is needed to keep track of the nodes discovered so far along a specified branch which helps in backtracking of the graph
     , and DFS may use hash table used to keep track of the visited vertices.

⚙️ [Worse-case] Time complexity
   - O(|V| + |E|): In the case that explicit graphs is traversed without repetition.
   - O(b^d): In the case of implicit graphs.
⚙️ [Worse-case] Space complexity
   - O(|V|): In the case that explicit graphs is traversed without repetition.
   - O(longest path length searched) = O(b*d): In the case of implicit graphs without elimination of duplicate nodes.
Best Average Worst Memory
- - |V| + |E| | b^d |V|

: 🍡 <Optimization algorithms>
🅰️ SubsetSumProblem
: 💻 Complexity Class of the decision problem is NP-Hard and weak NP-Complete.

     Time complexity can be thought as O(N*(B-A)).
         - Let A be the sum of the negative values and B the sum of the positive values.
         - This algorithm is polynomial in the values of A and B, which are exponential in their numbers of bits.
             so it includes pseudo-polynomial time algorithm.

     : 🍡 Horowitz and Sahni version, Three sum variant.
    
HorowitzSahniVersion
Variant of Horowitz and Sahni version

⚙️ I used additionally binary search to find target-sum T
   from this operation: ⏲️ 2^(n/2) * log_2( 2^(n/2) ) = 2^(n/2) * (n/2)
Best Average Worst Memory
- - n/2 * 2^(n/2) 2^(n/2)

🅰️ InsertionSorts
: 🍡 Insertion sort, Shellsort, Splaysort, Tree sort, Lsibrary sort, Patience sorting
InsertionSort
Properties🔪 comparison-based, Adaptive, Stable, In-place, Online
methods🔪 Insertion
elapsed time verification
0.04563570022583007812 [True, 'ascending']
⚙️ [Worse-case] Time complexity: ( O(N^2) comparisons )
   - The set of all worst case inputs consists of all arrays where each element is the smallest or second-smallest of the elements before it.
   - In these cases, every iteration of the inner loop will scan and shift the entire sorted subsection of the array before inserting the next element
   - Example: an array sorted in reverse order⚙️ [Best-case] Time complexity: ( O(N) comparisons, O(1) swaps) in the case of already sorted list

⚙️ Adaptive: the time complexity is O(kn) when each element in the input is no more than k places away from its sorted position.
Best Average Worst Memory
n n^2 n^2 1

: 🍡 Selection sort, Heapsort, Smoothsort, Cartesian tree sort, Tournament sort, Cycle sort, Weak-heap sort
HeapSort
Properties🔪 comparison-based, In-place
methods🔪 Selection
sift method🔪 sift down
elapsed time verification
0.00561952590942382812 [True, 'ascending']
⚙️ [Worse-case] Time complexity: O(n*log(n))
   - The method is run once, and is O(n) in performance.
   - The method is O(log n), and is called n times.
   = Therefore, the performance of this algorithm is O(n + n log n) = O(n log n).
Best Average Worst Memory
n*log(n) n*log(n) n*log(n) 1
SelectionSort
Properties🔪 comparison-based, In-place
methods🔪 Selection
elapsed time verification
0.04181480407714843750 [True, 'ascending']
⚙️ [Worse-case] Time complexity: ( O(N^2) comparisons, O(N) swaps )
   - Selecting the minimum requires scanning n elements (taking n-1 comparisons) and then swapping it into the first position. and n-2 ... so on.

⚙️ It is useful where swapping cost is very expensive and when write performance is a limiting factor.
Best Average Worst Memory
n n^2 n^2 1

Operators

   'a == b == c' equals 'a == b and b == c'.

⚙️ Left Shift (<<) operation is slightly faster than Exponentiation (**) operation.
   and Exponentiation (**) operation faster than math.pow().

⚙️ Sequence operation (s*n or n*s) is faster than List comprehension.
   ⚠️ Note that the List multiplication uses shallow copy.
   if then, [[dict()] * m for _ in range(n)] will share one dictionary.

Masking
Assume that
   - vertices are Integer equal or greater than 0.
   - vertex 0 is not used (if that is used, ** operation must be used instead of bitwise operation.).
-
var eval print
n (vertices) = 4
routes (bitwise) [bin(x)[2:] for x in range(1, 1 << n - 1)] ['1', '10', '11', '100', '101', '110', '111']
routes (actual) list(range(1, 1 << n - 1)) [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7]
vertices (bitwise) [bin(1 << v - 1)[2:] for v in range(1, n)] ['1', '10', '100']
vertices (actual) list(range(1, n)) [1, 2, 3]
❔ check <vertex> in <route> 1 << v - 1 & route != 0
❔ traversed Vertices in <route> [v for v in range(1, n) if 1 << (v - 1) & route]
❔ exclude a <vertex> in <route> route & ~(1 << v - 1)

===== wbfw109.labs.design_patterns =====
Interning
⚙️ Interning is re-using objects of equal value on-demand instead of creating new objects.
   - Interned objects must be immutable.
   - ⭕ Interning saves memory and can thus improve performance and memory footprint of a program.
     The downside is time required to search for existing values of objects which are to be interned.

⚙️ in Python, refer to https://docs.python.org/3/library/sys.html#sys.intern
   - It seems that immutable objects in function scope automatically interned.
     in global scope, only string not including whitespace or other primitive objects is automatically interned.
Creational pattern 🔪 Interning
eval print note
(a == b, a is b) (True, True) a = (1, 2); b = (1, 2)
(a == b, a is b) (True, True) a = 'abcd'; b = 'abcd'
(a == b, a is b) (True, True) a = 'ab cd'; b = 'ab cd'
(a == b, a is b) (True, True) a = sys.intern('ab cd'); b = sys.intern('ab cd')
